<TEXT>
mayor tommy hazouri at the controls 
of a crane wielding a wrecking ball officially marked the end of 
36 years of toll bridges in jacksonville by helping demolish 
several toll booths 
after collecting some 370 million in tolls from 15 billion 
motorists the tolls were removed friday from four local bridges 
and a fourlane expressway 
we have taken a quantum leap forward in improving the quality 
of life for our city today is like new years christmas and the 
fourth of july rolled into one hazouri said at ceremonies at the 
mathews bridge which opened in 1953 
moments earlier signs were unveiled on the mathews bridge toll 
plazas reading no tolls pass thru 
at the same time the tolls also ended on the fuller warren 
trout river and hart bridges and on butler boulevard a fourlane 
expressway linking interstate 95 to the beach 
there was a festive party atmosphere on the mathews bridge with 
crowds cheering horns honking and the st johns river city band 
playing fireworks were ignited on quarantine island in the middle 
of the st johns river 
the mayor and chester stokes chairman of the jacksonville 
transportation authority climbed aboard a large yellow crane and 
with the help of a crane operator toppled several toll booths 
in a large frontpage headline the florida timesunion 
proclaimed friday untolled joy keep the change 
the removal of the tolls was made possible by the passage in 
march 1988 of a halfcent city sales tax in addition to removing 
tolls on existing bridges the new dames point bridge opened 
tollfree earlier this year 
the removal of the tolls cames 18 months after the voters 
approved the concept the wait was necessary to convince state 
officials that the sales tax revenue would generate sufficient 
funds to cover the refinancing of 200 million in outstanding 
tollrevenue bonds issued in 1963 1977 and 1985 
</TEXT>
