<TEXT>
the justice department is hardening its 
assessment of the damage done by public disclosure to its 
investigation of suspected soviet spy felix s bloch 
justice department spokesman david runkel said flatly friday 
that the july 21 disclosure that the 54yearold us diplomat was 
under investigation had compromised the investigation 
there is no doubt that the premature disclosure of that case 
the premature disclosure that there was an ongoing investigation 
did compromise the investigation runkel said 
he didnt explain how the investigation had been compromised 
however runkels assessment was much stronger than one he 
delivered july 31 when asked about the impact of unprecedented 
publicity on an espionage investigation that so far has produced no 
criminal charges 
he said then that the premature disclosure may have had an 
adverse impact on the development of new evidence in the case 
the investigation of bloch the no 2 us diplomat in vienna 
for much of the decade was disclosed july 21 by abc news 
the differences in the statements reflects a different view 
based on how people in the department see the situation today 
runkel said friday when asked about the contrast between his two 
assessments 
he acknowledged the justice department opposed the state 
departments decision to issue a statement after the abc news 
broadcast that essentially confirmed the accuracy of the report 
the television report and a series of disclosures have produced 
what runkel called the circus going on out there of reporters 
and fbi agents tailing bloch each day on daily excursions from his 
apartment 
on thursday runkel acknowledged the department doesnt have an 
espionage case against bloch who was placed on paid leave by the 
state department 
asked why there were no charges despite continuous fbi 
surveillance of bloch runkel said the department does not bring 
charges unless it believes it has sufficient evidence to convince a 
jury beyond a reasonable doubt that a person is guilty of violating 
the law 
the fbi has been conducting a roundtheclock surveillance of 
bloch to prevent him from leaving the country while investigators 
try to find evidence to charge him with espionage 
runkel refused to comment when asked if the department had 
evidence that it was unwilling to disclose in court for fear of 
hurting counterintelligence operations 
bloch meantime led reporters and photographers on a friday 
afternoon shopping excursion to a suburban supermarket 
about 1 pm bloch announced he was about to leave his 
apartment two hours later bloch finally emerged driving his 
lightblue mercedezbenz he invited two television crews to ride 
along while he went on errands 
followed by a 20car caravan of reporters tv crews and fbi 
agents bloch drove to a shopping center in nearby bethesda md 
where he shopped at a supermarket and a bookstore 
the supermarket manager asked the tv crews to leave the store 
after a cameraman who was backpeddling to film bloch buying 
groceries knocked over an elderly woman who cut her hand on the 
floor 
</TEXT>
