<DOCNO> AP890812-0016 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
crash tests indicate that a driver of a 
peugeot 505s has a greater chance of head injury than drivers of 28 
other cars and small trucks tested so far federal engineers say 
however a peugeot spokesman said the tests conducted by the 
national highway traffic safety administration using 
instrumentequipped dummies dont accurately test the effects of 
real highway accidents 
our top concern is protecting human beings not dummies 
pascal henault president of peugeot motors of america said friday 
the new series of tests included 10 different car and van models 
by us and foreign automaker in previous tests involving 19 
vehicles the chevrolet astro van fared worst the astro now stands 
second among cars tested for injuries in a 35mileperhour 
collision 
the vehicles were tested under nhtsas program to provide 
consumers a guide to the safety of 1989 cars and small trucks 
the car in which the lightest injury potential was recorded so 
far is the dodge daytona followed by the ford thunderbird and the 
audi 80 the audi was among the 10 cars tested in the most recent 
round others in addition to the peugeot 505s were volkswagen 
fox hyundai sonata isuzu trooper ii suzuki sidekick and toyota 
cressida corolla pickup and van 
after the latest tests were made public peugeot issued a news 
release including comments from henault and from four automotive 
and consumer experts who criticized the government tests as 
inaccurate measures of the varied circumstances that exist in real 
crashes 
peugeots commitment to building cars that are safe in the 
real world cannot be overshadowed by these experimental crashtest 
results said henault 
the nhtsa tests consist of crashing a single model of each car 
containing two crash dummies into a fixed barrier at 35 mph the 
stresses that result on the dummies are measured by sensors the 
artificial occupants are protected by seat belts and other safety 
devices used in the cars 
nhtsa engineers reported stresses on the head as an index called 
the head injury criterion the higher the index the greater 
the likelihood of injury 
the peugeot crash produced a head injury criterion of 1983 on 
the driverside dummy the earlier astro test registered 1849 
federal regulations require cars to produce a head injury 
criterion no greater than 1000 in tests conducted by the 
automakers at 30 mph the nhtsa tests are not considered comparable 
because they are done at a speed 5 mph faster 
the tests are continuing but here is how all models so far 
tested rank in head injury criterion to the driver 
peugeot 505s 1983 chevrolet astro van 1849 toyota pickup 
1520 dodge spirit 1421 suzuki sidekick 1345 chevrolet 
caprice 1328 suzuki trooper ii 1269 toyota van 1183 
hyundai sonata 1196 toyota corolla and ford bronco ii 994 
mitsubishi galant 971 ford probe 970 jeep cherokee 968 
mitsubishi mirage 960 
others were the mercury tracer 940 eagle premier 877 lincoln 
continental 863 chevrolet s10 blazer 834 mitsubishi van 805 
toyota cressida 790 volkswagen fox 787 chrysler 5th avenue 
786 honda civic crx 750 eagle medallion 745 plymouth acclaim 
663 audi 80 600 ford thunderbird 541 dodge daytona 399 
</TEXT>
